<h2>
    <strong>Licenses, Regulations &amp; Conservation</strong>
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Angling license (12+ years)</strong> required.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Barbless hook rule</strong> enforced on catch-and-release waters.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Slot limits</strong> on Crane Prairie (8–14")
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Fly-only zones</strong>: Hosmer, Metolius section above Bridge 99.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Support conservation</strong> by practicing leave-no-trace and attending local restoration events&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    <strong>FAQs About Trout Fishing Near Bend</strong>
</h2>
<p>
    <strong>Q1: What's the easiest river to fish from town?</strong><br>
    <i>Crooked River</i> is ~27 miles away and ideal for beginners, guided or solo .
</p>
<p>
    <strong>Q2: Do I need a boat to fish Crane Prairie?</strong><br>
    Boat or float tube improves access, but shore fishing is possible near dams and inlets.
</p>
<p>
    <strong>Q3: Are trout stocked near Bend?</strong><br>
    Yes—local ponds and the Crooked are annually stocked; wild trout dominate in rivers.
</p>
<p>
    <strong>Q4: When is the best time to fish the Deschutes?</strong><br>
    Fall is top for browns; spring and summer handle dry-drop fishing well.
</p>
<p>
    <strong>Q5: What's required for Metolius fishing?</strong><br>
    Fly-only above Bridge 99; artificial lures allowed below.
</p>
<p>
    <strong>Q6: Can kids fish near Bend?</strong><br>
    Absolutely—Pine Nursery &amp; Shevlin ponds are youth-focused stockers with a two-fish daily&nbsp;
</p>
